Sentence: Ses01F_script03_1_F001 [008.7400-015.2000]: Freda is the only one who knows we are here.
She wouldn't ring up.
Ses01F_script03_1_M002 [014.6400-017.4300]: It must be them then.
Ses01F_script03_1_F002 [017.2000-022.7100]: It had to happen sooner or later.
What are we going to do?
Ses01F_script03_1_M004 [022.1600-024.9500]: We are okay, aren't we darling?
Ses01F_script03_1_F003 [024.4700-027.4400]: Now and always, sweet.
Ses01F_script03_1_M005 [026.8600-029.5200]: I don't care then.
Ses01F_script03_1_F004 [028.9600-032.9400]: It had to happen sooner or later.
Hello?
I'm sorry, what's that?
Wrong number.
[LAUGHTER]
Ses01F_script03_1_F005 [041.1700-047.6400]: [LAUGHTER] That sent shivers up my spine.
Ses01F_script03_1_M008 [046.7200-051.9842]: What shall we do if they suddenly walk in on us.
[LAUGHTER]
Ses01F_script03_1_F006 [051.2835-053.8175]: We'll behave exquisitely.
Ses01F_script03_1_M009 [053.2800-055.3300]: With perfect poise.
Ses01F_script03_1_F007 [054.6100-056.8000]: I think I shall do a curtsy.
Ses01F_script03_1_M010 [056.3700-064.4300]: It's strange; things that ought to matter dreadfully, they just don't matter at all when one's happy.
Do they?
The pity is that one can't stay happy.
Ses01F_script03_1_M011 [066.8400-069.2900]: Darling, don't say that.
I think the whole thing's a cruel joke.
This beautiful and sacred thing - love?
Meaning just that.
Ses01F_script03_1_M013 [076.3200-086.5180]: Well what does it all mean?
That's what I ask myself in my quest for ultimate truth.
Dear God, what does it all mean?
Ses01F_script03_1_F011 [084.4700-088.2600]: Don't laugh at me.
I'm being serious.
Ses01F_script03_1_M014 [087.7600-092.5700]: Oh darling, you mustn't be serious.
It's just what they want.
Ses01F_script03_1_M015 [093.2300-100.1600]: All of those futile moralists who make life unbearable.
You have to laugh at them, be flippant.
Ses01F_script03_1_M016 [100.1950-106.5500]: You know, flippancy brings out the acid in their darned, light and sweetness.
Ses01F_script03_1_F013 [105.9400-109.3900]: you know if I laugh at everything then I must laugh at us, too.
We are figures of fun.
All right.
Ses01F_script03_1_F014 [112.4000-118.3800]: How long with it last, this ludicrous overbearing love of ours?
Ses01F_script03_1_F015 [120.0800-122.4300]: Shall we always want to bicker and fight?
That fire will fade along with our passion.
Ses01F_script03_1_F016 [126.1000-128.9675]: Oh dear, should we like that?
Ses01F_script03_1_M020 [128.3800-131.7700]: Well it depends on how well we've played.
Ses01F_script03_1_F017 [131.8800-136.8000]: What happens if one of us dies?
Does the other one still laugh?
Yes with all of his might.
Ses01F_script03_1_F018 [139.9400-142.6900]: Well that's serious enough, isn't it?
no.
Death is a very laughable thing.
It's a cunning little mystery, it's all done with mirrors.
Ses01F_script03_1_F019 [149.9500-153.0800]: I think you are talking nonsense.
So is everyone, in the long run.
Ses01F_script03_1_M024 [155.1150-167.7000]: Let's be superficial, and just pity those poor philosophers, huh?
Let's blow trumpets and squeakers and enjoy the party for as long as we can, you know, like small, idiotic school children.
Ses01F_script03_1_M025 [168.6900-176.2700]: Oh Come and kiss me darling before your body rots and worms pop out of your eye sockets.
Ses01F_script03_1_F021 [174.8825-178.8500]: Oh Elliott, worms don't pop.
Ses01F_script03_1_M026 [178.9700-195.6000]: Oh See, I don't care what you do, see.
You can paint yourself green and run naked through the Place Vendome and run off with all of the men of the world.
I shan't say a word, just as long as you love me best.
Thank you, darling.
The same applies to you too, except that if you so much as look at another woman I'll kill you.
Ses01F_script03_1_M027 [204.5900-210.7575]: Do you remember that awful scene we had in Venice?
Ses01F_script03_1_F023 [208.8925-211.4200]: Which particular one?
Ses01F_script03_1_M028 [211.0300-215.8300]: The one where you put that tiny painted wooden snake in my bed.
Ses01F_script03_1_F024 [215.2800-220.3500]: Oh Charles, that was his name.
He did wiggle so beautifully.
Ses01F_script03_1_M030 [219.2200-221.8200]: It was a terrible thing.
I hated it.
Ses01F_script03_1_F025 [221.1200-226.8700]: I know you did.
You threw him out the window into the Grand Canal.
I'll never forgive you for that.
Ses01F_script03_1_M031 [226.3200-228.8900]: How long did that row last?
Ses01F_script03_1_F026 [228.3700-231.0700]: It went on intermittently for days.
Ses01F_script03_1_M033 [232.1675-238.4900]: But the worst one was in Cannes when your curling irons burnt a hole in my new dressing gown.
Ses01F_script03_1_F027 [237.4000-242.2600]: Oh And it burnt my comb, too, and all of those towels in the bathroom.
Ses01F_script03_1_M034 [241.6000-245.8700]: That was a rouser, wasn't it?
Ses01F_script03_1_F028 [244.0875-248.0700]: [LAUGHTER] That was the first time you hit me.
Ses01F_script03_1_M035 [247.7400-250.7000]: I did not hit you very hard.
Ses01F_script03_1_F029 [250.2200-262.4300]: The manager came in, he found us rolling about the floor, biting and scratching like panthers.
[LAUGHTER]  How utterly, utterly ridiculous.
Ses01F_script03_1_M036 [256.8500-262.0325]: [LAUGHTER] I'll never forget his face.
[LAUGHTER]
Ses01F_script03_1_M037 [262.3975-267.4500]: [LAUGHTER] We were very much younger then.
Ses01F_script03_1_F030 [262.4600-269.6400]: [LAUGHTER] And very much sillier.
Ses01F_script03_1_M038 [271.6400-276.2000]: However I believe the real cause of that row was Peter Burden.
You knew there was nothing in that.
